  "prompt": "Why does the RBI increase the repo rate during inflation and decrease it during deflation?",
  "response": "The Reserve Bank of India (RBI) adjusts the repo rate as a monetary policy tool to manage inflation and economic growth. Here's why they increase or decrease the repo rate:\n\nDuring Inflation:\n1. When repo rate increases:\n- Borrowing becomes more expensive for banks\n- Banks raise interest rates for customers\n- Reduces money supply in the economy\n- Discourages excessive spending\n- Encourages saving\n- Helps slow down economic activity\n- Reduces inflationary pressures\n\nDuring Deflation:\n1. When repo rate decreases:\n- Borrowing becomes cheaper for banks\n- Banks lower interest rates for customers\n- Increases money supply in the economy\n- Encourages spending and investment\n- Stimulates economic growth\n- Helps counter deflationary trends\n- Makes credit more accessible\n\nMechanism:\n- Higher repo rate \u2192 Less liquidity \u2192 Reduced money circulation \u2192 Lower inflation\n- Lower repo rate \u2192 More liquidity \u2192 Increased money circulation \u2192 Economic stimulus\n\nPurpose:\n- Maintain price stability\n- Control money supply\n- Manage economic growth\n- Regulate overall economic conditions\n\nThe RBI uses repo rate as a key instrument to balance economic growth and price stability.",
